# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1876 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] It was the team's first season of existence, having been formed as part of the brand new National League in 1876.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] This team was not related (except by name) to the previous Cincinnati Red Stockings National Association team, which had folded in 1870.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] One bright spot for the Reds was the play of Charley Jones, who led the club with a batting average of .286, had the second highest home run total in the league with four, and was among the league leaders in doubles and slugging percentage.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds played their first ever game on April 25, 1876, defeating the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Brown Stockings 2–1 at Avenue Grounds.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Wins would be few and far between for the Reds, as after putting up a solid 3–2 record in their opening five games, the Reds would go on an eleven-game losing streak to fall to 3–13.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] After defeating the Hartford Dark Blues 8–2 to end their losing streak, the Reds would then have a thirteen-game losing streak, and saw their record fall to 4–26.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] By the time the season was finished, Cincinnati had the worst record in the National League, as they ended the season with a 9–56 record, 42.5 games behind the first place Chicago White Stockings.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1877 Cincinnati Reds season** was the team's second season in the National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished sixth and last in the league with a record of 15–42, 25½ games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing dead last in the National League in the 1876 season, the Reds attempted to improve their club by signing Lip Pike, who spent the previous season with the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike was also named the manager of the team.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds got off to another terrible start, as they had a 3–11 start to the season, and Pike stepped down as the manager.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team was briefly disbanded by owner Josiah Keck, and although a group of eight businessmen stepped in to rescue the franchise, some Cincinnati players had been signed by other teams in the interim, and some newspapers subsequently refused to list the Red's results.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Bob Addy took over as player manager; however, he too saw very few wins as Cincinnati went 5–19 during his managerial stint.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Jack Manning then finished the year as player-manager, going 7–12, as the Reds had a 15–42 record and once again finished in the National League cellar, 25.5 games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another solid season for the Reds, hitting .310 with two homers and a team high 36 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Manning also had a solid year, hitting .317, as he had a team high 80 hits while tying Jones with a team high 36 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike hit .298 with a team high four home runs, and added 23 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, rookie Bobby Mitchell came up late in the season and was very impressive, leading Cincinnati with six victories and a team best 3.51 ERA in twelve games.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1878 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished second in the National League with a record of 37–23, four games behind the Boston Red Caps.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing their first two seasons in the National League in last place, the Reds were hoping for some improvement in the 1878 season.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Cal McVey of the Chicago White Stockings to become the team's new third baseman, and new manager.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Catcher Deacon White of the Boston Red Caps signed with Cincinnati.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White led the National League with a .387 batting average, 103 hits, eleven triples, 49 RBI, and a .545 slugging percentage with the Red Caps in 1877.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White also led the National League with 60 RBI while playing for the White Stockings in 1876.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, 23-year-old Will White was signed by the Reds.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White appeared in three games with the Boston Red Caps in 1877, going 2–1 with a 3.00 ERA.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another very solid season with the Reds, as he had a .310 batting average, along with a team high three home runs and 39 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White saw his production slip, however, he still hit .314 with 29 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Player-manager McVey was solid with a .306 average and two home runs along with 28 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White had a spectacular season, going 30–21 with a 1.79 ERA in 468 innings pitched.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds opened the season with a six-game winning streak, and stayed hot in their first twenty games, going 15–5, and were sitting in first place in the National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati then went on a six-game losing streak, falling to 15–11, and out of first place.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds never reclaimed first place; however, they finished the season strong, including a nine-game winning streak late in the year, to finish in second place with a 37–23 record, five games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1879 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fifth in the National League with a record of 43–37, 14 games behind the Providence Grays.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds were hoping to build off a great 1878 season, in which the team finished in second place in the National League with a 37–23 record.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In the off-season, the Reds announced that catcher Deacon White would become the player-manager.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Ross Barnes to play shortstop.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Barnes had missed most of the 1877 season and all of the 1878 season after falling ill.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In his last full season in 1876, Barnes played with the Chicago White Stockings, and led the NL with a .429 batting average, 138 hits, 126 runs, 38 doubles, and fourteen triples.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] King Kelly had a very solid season, hitting .348 with two home runs and 47 RBI, while another youngster, twenty-year-old Buttercup Dickerson, hit .291 with two home runs and a team high 57 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Deacon White rebounded from a poor 1878 season by his standards, as he hit .330 with a homer and 52 RBI.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, Will White led the NL with 75 starts, as he had a 43–31 record with a 1.99 ERA in his league high 680 innings pitched.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati started off hot, as they opened the season with a five-game winning streak.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] However, the club lost seven of their next eight games to fall under .500.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati had a mediocre 9–9 record after eighteen games, and player-manager Deacon White turned over his managerial duties to Cal McVey, who had been the Reds' player-manager in 1878.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati lost the first five games under McVey, however, the team began to play better, and ended the season with a 43–37 record, fifth in the league, and fourteen games behind the first-place Grays.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/19th-century-national-league-teams] The following is a list of United States **Major League Baseball teams that played in the National League during the 19th century**.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/19th-century-national-league-teams] None of these teams, other than Athletic and Mutual, had actual names during this period; sportswriters however often applied creative monickers which are still, mistakenly, used today as "team names" following a convention established in 1951.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/19th-century-national-league-teams] This lineup of teams remained the same from 1892 to the end of the 1899 season.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/19th-century-national-league-teams] After the 1899 season Baltimore, Cleveland, Louisville and Washington were dropped from the National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/19th-century-national-league-teams] This lineup remained the same until Boston relocated to Milwaukee in 1953.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The **American Association of Base Ball Clubs** (**AA**) was a professional baseball league that existed for 10 seasons from 1882 to 1891.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Together with the National League (NL), founded in 1876, the AA participated in an early version of the World Series seven times versus the champion of the NL in an interleague championship playoff tournament.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] At the end of its run, several AA franchises joined the NL.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] After 1891, the NL existed alone, with each season's champions being awarded the Temple Cup (1894–1897).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] During its existence, the AA was often simply referred to as "the Association" in the media, in contrast to the NL, which was sometimes called "the League".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] It was also sometimes called the "Beer and Whiskey League".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The American Association (AA) distinguished itself in several ways from what it considered to be the puritanical National League (NL).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The new league established teams in what the NL leaders pejoratively called "river cities", including Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Louisville and St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Louis, with the inherent implication of lower morality or social standards in those cities.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] In contrast to the NL, the AA offered cheaper ticket prices, Sunday games and alcoholic beverages to its patrons.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] On November 8, 1881, at the Gibson House in Cincinnati, it was decided that individual teams in the league-to-be would operate their own affairs and set their own admission prices, under an agreement called the "guarantee system".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The NL at that time prohibited the sale of alcohol on its grounds, while the AA had no such restrictions, especially as several of its teams were backed by breweries and distilleries.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The AA became known as "The Beer and Whiskey League", another pejorative term applied by NL owners, which did not seem to bother the fans of the Association's clubs.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Beginning in 1884 and continuing through 1890, the champion of the AA met the champion of the NL in an early version of the World Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] These early Series were less organized than the modern version, with as few as three games played and as many as fifteen, and the contests of 1885 and 1890 ending in disputed ties.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The NL won four of these Series, while the AA won only one, in 1886 when the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Louis Cardinals) defeated the Chicago White Stockings (now the Chicago Cubs).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Over its lifetime, the AA was weakened by several factors.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] One was the tendency of some of its teams to jump to the NL.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The consistently stronger NL was in better position to survive adverse conditions.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Some owners of AA teams also owned a NL team.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The most significant blow to the AA was dealt by the Players' League, a third major league formed in 1890, which siphoned off talent and gate receipts.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] In a rare historical oddity, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (now the Los Angeles Dodgers) won the league's championship and represented the AA in the 1889 World Series, switched to the NL during the off-season, and then repeated the same feat.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] No player who spent the majority of his career in the AA is in the baseball Hall of Fame, although Bid McPhee of the Cincinnati Reds played eight of his eighteen seasons in the AA before the Reds moved to the National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The living legacy of the old Association is the group of teams that came over to the National League to stay.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The Pirates moved to the NL after the 1886 season, the Bridegrooms/Dodgers and the Cincinnati Reds after the 1889 season, and the Browns/Cardinals after the American Association folded following the 1891 season.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Following the reorganization and contraction of the NL from 12 teams down to 8 in 1900, half of the eight surviving teams were former members of the AA.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Several of the AA's home-field venues survived into the 1960s: The ballpark used by the 1891 Washington club evolved into Griffith Stadium; the home of the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Louis Browns, Sportsman's Park; and the city block occupied by the Reds, which evolved into Crosley Field.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Other than the clubs themselves, Crosley Field was the last physical remnant of the AA—it was the home field of the Cincinnati Reds until mid-season 1970 and was razed in April 1972.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] During the AA's existence, four clubs defected over to the NL: Allegheny City (joined NL 1887, later became the Pittsburgh Pirates), the Cleveland Spiders (joined NL 1889), the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (joined NL 1890, eventually renamed the Dodgers), and the Cincinnati Reds (joined NL 1890).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] At the AA's demise in 1891, four additional clubs joined the NL: the St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Louis Browns (later the Cardinals), the Louisville Colonels, the Washington Statesmen (renamed the Senators), and the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] Therefore, from 1892 to 1899, when the NL consisted of 12 teams, 8 of them had been former AA clubs.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] All four have posted more than 10,000 all-time major-league victories.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] AA statistics are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB), the AA being one of six leagues deemed "major" by the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball in 1969.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The first line is the formation of the American Association (AA) in 1882, and the second marks the end of the American Association.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] World's Championship Series championships are shown with a "•", American Association Pennants in non-World Championship Series seasons are shown with a "#", and American Association Pennant winners who tied or lost the World Championship Series are shown with a "^".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] For the 1891 season, the Philadelphia Athletics were replaced by the Philadelphia Quakers of the Player's League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] The 1891 Cincinnati Kelly's Killers folded during the season and were replaced by the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-association-1882-1891] All non-American Association labels not labeled "NL" (National League) or "PL" (Players' League) are minor league teams.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster] The following is a list of players and who appeared in at least one game for the **Cincinnati Reds** franchise, which played in the National League from 1876 to 1879.
[src:cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster/cincinnati-reds-1876-1879-all-time-roster] For players from the current Cincinnati Reds, see Cincinnati Reds all-time roster.
